to the tachyon evolving between two different minima of the
potential. Possible initial conditions (at ) for these
solutions are of the form  T (0) = const.   ,  T(0)=0  . Another set of
solutions corresponds to a tachyon evolution with _t  T(t) =   , where  and  lead to equivalent solutions.
Appropriate boundary conditions for the tachyon (at ) are
then of the form  T (0) = 0  , 
T(0)= const.  In this section we characterize the
supergravity solutions generated by a tachyonic source with the
properties mentioned above. The results we present are for
solutions with boundary conditions () and asymptotic
behavior (). We have found that the solutions associated
with the boundary conditions () and asymptotic behavior
() have similar qualitative features. Strictly speaking,
our approach to studying real-time evolution in supergravity can
also be extended to more general cases, i.e. , brane decay or
creation (half SD-branes). file=potential.eps,
